const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'tripLength', header: 'Max Trip Length' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Age Limit' },
  { key: 'preExisting', header: 'Pre-Existing' },
  { key: 'bestFor', header: 'Best For' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'GeoBlue Voyager', tripLength: '364 days', ageLimit: '84', preExisting: 'Stable 6 months', bestFor: 'US snowbirds to Mexico/Caribbean' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', tripLength: '364 days', ageLimit: '74 (80 renewal)', preExisting: 'With underwriting', bestFor: 'Long stays, comprehensive needs' },
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', tripLength: 'Unlimited', ageLimit: '74 (lifetime renewal)', preExisting: 'With underwriting', bestFor: 'Full expat coverage' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Travel', tripLength: '180 days', ageLimit: '100+', preExisting: 'Waiver available', bestFor: 'Canadian snowbirds to US' },
  { provider: 'Manulife', tripLength: '212 days', ageLimit: '89', preExisting: 'Stable 90-180 days', bestFor: 'Canadian snowbirds, affordable' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Snowbirds 2026 | Part-Time Expat Coverage"
  description="Compare health insurance for snowbirds and part-time expats. Coverage for those splitting time between home country and warmer destinations."
  headline="Best Health Insurance for Snowbirds"
  subheadline="Spending winters in Florida, Mexico, Spain, or Thailand? You need insurance that covers you abroad without losing your home country benefits—here's how to get both."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Snowbird Quotes →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Snowbirds face unique insurance challenges: you need coverage abroad for extended stays, but you're not fully relocating. You want to maintain home country coverage for when you return. And many snowbirds are seniors with health considerations that complicate insurance.
  </p>

  <p>
    After analyzing options for part-time expats, here are our recommendations:
  </p>

  <h3>Best for US Snowbirds Going South: GeoBlue Voyager</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The good:</strong> Blue Cross Blue Shield backing, covers trips up to 364 days, excellent for Mexico, Caribbean, and Central America. Pre-existing condition coverage for stable conditions. Strong evacuation coverage.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The limits:</strong> More expensive than basic travel medical. Some destinations require higher-tier plans. Age 85+ excluded from new enrollment.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> American retirees wintering in Mexico, Costa Rica, or Caribbean islands who want solid coverage with a familiar brand.
  </p>

  <h3>Best for Canadian Snowbirds: Manulife or Allianz</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The good:</strong> Designed specifically for Canadian snowbirds going to US/Mexico. Integrates with provincial health coverage. Pre-existing condition waivers available. Competitive pricing for seniors.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Provincial health requirements vary—typically must spend 6+ months in Canada. Trip length limits may not cover full winter stays.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Canadian retirees spending winters in Florida, Arizona, or Mexico while maintaining provincial health coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Best for Full Dual Coverage: Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>The good:</strong> True international health insurance that works in both locations equally. No trip length limits. Lifetime renewal once enrolled. Covers you whether home or abroad.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Premium pricing—often $500-800+/month for seniors. May duplicate home country coverage. Most comprehensive but most expensive.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Snowbirds who split time fairly evenly or want seamless coverage without managing multiple policies.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Snowbird Insurance Quotes"
    description="Compare plans for part-time expats and seasonal travelers."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="snowbird-needs">What Snowbirds Actually Need</h2>
  <p>
    Your insurance needs depend on your snowbird pattern:
  </p>

  <h3>The Classic Winter Escape (3-6 months abroad)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary coverage:</strong> Keep your home country insurance (Medicare, provincial health, NHS, etc.)</li>
    <li><strong>Travel medical:</strong> Add coverage for your time abroad—emergency care, hospitalization, evacuation</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> Critical for seniors—ensure your conditions are covered or at least stabilized</li>
    <li><strong>Trip length:</strong> Verify policy covers your entire stay, including extensions</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The Extended Stay (6+ months abroad)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Home coverage risk:</strong> Extended absence may affect home country entitlements (Medicare, provincial health)</li>
    <li><strong>Consider full expat insurance:</strong> At 6+ months, international health insurance often makes more sense than travel medical</li>
    <li><strong>Tax residency:</strong> Longer stays may have tax implications—insurance is just one consideration</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The Split Life (roughly 50/50)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Dual coverage:</strong> You need real coverage in both places, not just emergency travel medical</li>
    <li><strong>Global plans:</strong> Cigna Global, BUPA, Allianz cover you regardless of location</li>
    <li><strong>Coordination:</strong> Some conditions may be better treated in one location—ensure both are fully covered</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Key Concerns for Snowbirds</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> Most snowbirds have some health history. Coverage varies dramatically—from full exclusion to coverage after stability periods.</li>
    <li><strong>Age limits:</strong> Many travel medical policies stop at 70 or 75. Know the limits before you need to renew.</li>
    <li><strong>Evacuation:</strong> If something serious happens, can you get home or to appropriate care? Evacuation coverage is essential.</li>
    <li><strong>Prescription coverage:</strong> Ongoing medications need to be covered or affordable locally.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="how-we-evaluated">How We Evaluated</h2>
  <p>
    We focused on factors that matter for snowbirds and part-time expats:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pre-existing condition handling:</strong> How do they treat common senior conditions? Exclusions, stability periods, or full coverage?</li>
    <li><strong>Age limits:</strong> Can you get and keep coverage into your 70s, 80s, or beyond?</li>
    <li><strong>Trip length flexibility:</strong> Does coverage match snowbird patterns (3-6 months)?</li>
    <li><strong>Home country integration:</strong> Does it complement or conflict with Medicare, provincial health, etc.?</li>
    <li><strong>Network in destination:</strong> Are there direct billing options where you're actually going?</li>
    <li><strong>Claims experience:</strong> How do real seniors rate the claims process?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>GeoBlue Voyager</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue brings Blue Cross Blue Shield credibility to international coverage. For American snowbirds, this familiarity matters—you're dealing with a name you know, and the network connects to BCBS resources.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Voyager plans cover trips up to 364 days, accommodating even extended snowbird stays. Pre-existing conditions are covered if stable for 6 months prior—reasonable for most managed conditions like controlled diabetes or hypertension.
  </p>

  <p>
    Coverage includes emergency medical, hospital stays, emergency evacuation (unlimited), and medical repatriation. Prescription drugs related to covered conditions are included. Mental health coverage is available.
  </p>

  <p>
    Network coverage is strong in Mexico, Caribbean, and Central America—common snowbird destinations. The app works well for finding providers and initiating claims.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pricing:</strong> $150-400/month for seniors depending on age, destination, and coverage level. Not cheap, but solid coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best option for American snowbirds wanting Blue Cross familiarity with strong Mexico/Caribbean coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>IMG Global Medical Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    IMG offers comprehensive international coverage that works well for snowbirds wanting more than basic travel medical. Coverage up to $8M handles any realistic scenario.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pre-existing conditions can be covered with proper underwriting—disclosure is essential, but IMG is more flexible than some competitors. Maximum entry age is 74, with renewal to 80.
  </p>

  <p>
    The plan works globally, so whether you're in Mexico this year and Portugal next year, coverage travels with you. No trip limits—stay as long as you want.
  </p>

  <p>
    US coverage is available if you're a US citizen or resident, useful if you return home mid-season for treatment.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pricing:</strong> $200-500/month for seniors depending on age and coverage options. Competitive for comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Strong option for snowbirds wanting comprehensive coverage with flexibility on destination and trip length.
  </p>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    For snowbirds who truly live between two places, Cigna Global offers seamless coverage that works equally well in both locations. No trip limits, no primary/secondary residence complications—you're covered wherever you are.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is full international health insurance, not travel medical. You get proper health coverage including routine care, chronic condition management, specialists, and preventive care. For snowbirds with ongoing health needs, this matters.
  </p>

  <p>
    Maximum entry age is 74, but once enrolled, coverage continues for life regardless of health changes. This lifetime guarantee is valuable for seniors.
  </p>

  <p>
    The network is global—excellent in US, Europe, Mexico, Thailand, or wherever snowbirds go. Direct billing widely available.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pricing:</strong> $500-900/month for seniors depending on age and coverage modules. Premium pricing for premium coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Best for snowbirds who want one comprehensive plan covering both locations equally. Worth the premium if budget allows.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Travel Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz offers travel medical plans suitable for snowbird trips up to 180 days. Pre-existing condition waivers are available if purchased within certain windows of booking travel.
  </p>

  <p>
    Coverage is straightforward: emergency medical, evacuation, trip interruption. It's travel insurance, not comprehensive health coverage, but for healthy snowbirds on shorter stays, it works.
  </p>

  <p>
    Age limits are generous—coverage available into your 90s for some plans. This matters when other insurers cut off at 75 or 80.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pricing:</strong> $100-250/month depending on age, destination, and trip length. Affordable option for shorter stays.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Good budget option for shorter snowbird trips (under 180 days) with healthy travelers.
  </p>

  <h3>Manulife Travel Insurance (Canada)</h3>
  <p>
    Designed specifically for Canadian snowbirds, Manulife understands the unique needs of Canadians wintering in the US, Mexico, or Caribbean while maintaining provincial health coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Coverage for trips up to 212 days fits typical snowbird patterns. Pre-existing condition coverage requires stability for 90-180 days depending on plan. Coverage available up to age 89.
  </p>

  <p>
    Integrates with provincial health coverage—they understand OHIP, RAMQ, and other provincial requirements. Claims process is Canada-centric.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pricing:</strong> $100-300/month for seniors depending on age, stability period, and coverage level. Competitive for Canadian market.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Verdict:</strong> Top choice for Canadian snowbirds—built for your specific situation.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Snowbird Plans"
    description="Get quotes based on your destination and trip length."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="choosing-the-right-plan">Choosing the Right Plan</h2>

  <h3>By Nationality</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>American snowbirds:</strong> GeoBlue Voyager (Blue Cross familiarity) or IMG Global (comprehensive)</li>
    <li><strong>Canadian snowbirds:</strong> Manulife or Allianz (designed for provincial health integration)</li>
    <li><strong>British snowbirds:</strong> Cigna Global or Allianz Care (maintain NHS eligibility considerations)</li>
    <li><strong>European snowbirds:</strong> Allianz Care (European expertise) or Cigna Global</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>By Destination</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>US (Florida, Arizona, California):</strong> Manulife/Allianz for Canadians; GeoBlue for Americans</li>
    <li><strong>Mexico:</strong> GeoBlue (strong Mexico network) or IMG Global</li>
    <li><strong>Spain/Portugal:</strong> Allianz Care (European network) or Cigna Global</li>
    <li><strong>Thailand:</strong> Cigna Global (best Asia network) or Now Health</li>
    <li><strong>Caribbean:</strong> GeoBlue or IMG Global</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>By Health Situation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Healthy, no medications:</strong> Basic travel medical (Allianz Travel, SafetyWing) may suffice</li>
    <li><strong>Controlled conditions (diabetes, hypertension):</strong> GeoBlue, IMG, or Manulife with stability periods</li>
    <li><strong>Complex health history:</strong> Cigna Global with full underwriting—they can cover more</li>
    <li><strong>Recent health events:</strong> Wait for stability period, or accept exclusions</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Will I lose my Medicare/provincial health coverage?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Depends on how long you're away. Medicare continues if you maintain US residency. Canadian provincial health typically requires 6+ months residence in-province per year—extended snowbird trips may jeopardize coverage. Check your specific situation before leaving.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What counts as a pre-existing condition?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Generally, any condition for which you've received treatment, medication, or medical advice in the lookback period (typically 6-24 months). This includes controlled conditions like diabetes, heart disease, and high blood pressure. Stability periods require no changes to medication or symptoms.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I extend my coverage if I stay longer?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Most travel medical policies allow extensions if requested before expiration and if maximum trip length isn't exceeded. Some require you to remain healthy during the policy—a new condition during your trip may prevent extension. Annual international health insurance (Cigna, BUPA) has no trip limits.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I need to return home for treatment?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Emergency evacuation coverage handles medical emergencies requiring transport home. For non-emergency treatment preference, you'd typically use your home country coverage. Medical repatriation coverage helps coordinate return. Some comprehensive plans (Cigna) cover treatment in your home country equally.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I buy annual or single-trip coverage?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        If you take one extended trip per year, single-trip is usually cheaper. If you travel multiple times or want year-round flexibility, annual plans offer better value. For snowbirds who might return home mid-winter and go back, annual coverage provides flexibility.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about my prescription medications?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Bring sufficient supply from home—often 90-day prescriptions are available. Travel medical covers prescriptions related to covered conditions during your trip. For ongoing medications, verify local availability and pricing. Some snowbirds strategically fill prescriptions in Mexico or Canada where prices are lower.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Your Winter Escape?"
    description="Get quotes for snowbird coverage. Compare options for your destination and trip length."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> Insurance requirements vary by nationality, destination, and individual health circumstances. Extended travel may affect home country health entitlements—verify residency requirements with relevant authorities. Pre-existing condition coverage depends on individual underwriting. Always confirm coverage details and pricing directly with providers.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
